Here's a multi-form question based on the LaTeX code and explanation provided:

Question: Which of the following LaTeX commands would correctly add both a vertical line between columns 3 and 4 and a dotted diagonal line in the upper-right quadrant of the matrix shown in the image?

A) \CodeAfter
   \vline{3-4}
   \dotdiag{1-4}{3-6}

B) \CodeAfter
   \line{1-4}{3-6}
   \tikz \draw (1-|4) -- (7-|4);

C) \CodeAfter
   \hline{3-4}
   \Ddots{1-4}{3-6}

D) \CodeAfter
   \vline{4}
   \line{1-4}{3-6}

Correct Answer: B

Explanation: The correct answer is B. The \CodeAfter command is used to add extra drawing instructions after the matrix is constructed. The \line{1-4}{3-6} command draws the dotted diagonal line from cell (1,4) to cell (3,6). The \tikz \draw (1-|4) -- (7-|4); command uses TikZ to draw a vertical line from row 1 to row 7 along column 4. This combination accurately produces both the vertical line and the dotted diagonal as shown in the desired output image.

Option A is incorrect because \vline and \dotdiag are not valid commands in this context. Option C is incorrect because \hline would draw a horizontal line, not a vertical one, and \Ddots is not a valid command for drawing a diagonal line. Option D is close but uses an incorrect syntax for the vertical line command.

